{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"15041ed2-a8f4-454d-ade5-eb8f59b3eae6","content":"## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\n**1. Start the Inspector:**\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj`\n\n  *(Or if you have a built DLL: command = `dotnet`, args = `YourMcpServer.dll`)*\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector launches your server as a child process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Debug your tools:**\n- Use the **Tools** tab to list discovered tools, invoke them with sample inputs, and inspect JSON responses.\n- The **Messages** pane shows raw JSON-RPC traffic for deeper debugging.\n\n**⚠️ Key gotcha:** Your server **must not** write anything to stdout except MCP JSON-RPC messages. Use `stderr` for logging:\n```csharp\nConsole.Error.WriteLine(\"Debug info here\");\n```\nAny stray `Console.WriteLine()` will corrupt the protocol and cause connection failures.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"04321946-d939-463e-b675-a70105762ce1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to connect a C# MCP server (using stdio transport) to the MCP Inspector for interactive testing/debugging. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore their codebase. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":362},"id":"bb1872ab-198f-48c2-9ab1-be9e619f1d7a","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:50:50.926Z","parentId":"e3c11b08-2788-4c22-afc3-a1fd8f1309ab"}
